The paper is about a new architecture for convolutional neural networks (CNNs) that improves their performance on object recognition tasks. This is a topic that is highly relevant to computer vision (cs.CV) and machine learning (cs.LG). The paper also discusses how the new architecture addresses the vanishing-gradient problem, which is a common issue in deep neural networks, and this connects it to the subfield of neural networks (cs.NE). Additionally, the paper evaluates the proposed architecture on several benchmark datasets, which is a common practice in the field of artificial intelligence (cs.AI). Finally, the paper discusses how the new architecture encourages feature reuse, which is a topic that is relevant to natural language processing (cs.CL) as well as computer vision.
